    <section style="font-weight: bolder;font-size: xx-large;font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Tahoma, sans-serif;">
    <p>
    <u>HTML -(HyperText Markup Language) Detailed Overview:</u><br>
    HTML (HyperText Markup Language) is the standard language used to create and structure web<br>
    pages and web applications. It forms the backbone of all websites, defining the content,<br>
    structure, and basic formatting of a webpage. HTML is not a programming language but a markup<br>
    language used to define the layout and elements of a webpage using a system of tags and attributes.<br><br>
    </p>
    <hr>
    <hr>
    <figure>
    <img src="https://thumbs.dreamstime.com/b/round-linear-banner-html-concept-black-chalkboard-vector-thin-line-icons-coding-interner-computer-technology-modern-web-133564428.jpg" alt="incorrect image" height="400" width="400">
    </figure>
    <h1>✅ What is HTML?</h1>
    HyperText – Refers to the ability to link to other documents or web pages through hyperlinks.<br>
    Markup Language – A language that uses a set of tags to define the structure and presentation of content.<br><br>
    HTML allows you to create a structured document using elements such as:<br>
    *Headings<br>
    *Paragraphs<br>
    *Lists<br>
    *Links<br>
    *Images<br>
    *Forms<br>
    *Tables<br><br>
    </section>
    <section style="font-weight: bolder;font-size: xx-large;font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Tahoma, sans-serif;">
        🚀 <u>History of HTML</u><br>
        <ul>
       <li> HTML 1.0  – Introduced in 1993 by Tim Berners-Lee (basic text formatting and links).<br></li>
        <li>HTML 2.0  – Released in 1995 (added forms and tables).<br></li>
        <li>HTML 3.2  – Released in 1997 (added support for scripting and styles).<br></li>
        <lli>HTML 4.01– Released in 1999 (added support for multimedia).<br></li>
        <li>XHTML     – Released in early 2000s (more strict rules).<br></li>
        <li>HTML5     – Released in 2014 (introduced semantic elements, multimedia support, and enhanced APIs).<br><br></li>
       </ul>       
    </section>
    <section style="font-weight: bolder;font-size: xx-large;font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Tahoma, sans-serif;">
        💡 <u>Advantages of HTML</u><br>
        ✅ Simple and easy to learn.<br>
        ✅ Works across all browsers and platforms.<br>
        ✅ Supported by CSS and JavaScript for styling and interactivity.<br>
        ✅ Lightweight and fast to render.<br><br>
    </section>
    <section style="font-weight: bolder;font-size: xx-large;font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Tahoma, sans-serif;">
        🚫 <u>Limitations of HTML</u><br>
        ❌ No logic or dynamic behavior (requires JavaScript for that).<br>
        ❌ Limited in terms of design without CSS.<br><br>
    </section>
    <section style="font-weight: bolder;font-size: xx-large;font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Tahoma, sans-serif;">
        🔥 <u>Conclusion</u><br>
        HTML is the foundation of web development, providing the structure<br>
        and content for all web pages. Combined with CSS (for styling) and JavaScript (for interactivity),<br>
        HTML forms the core of modern web development.<br>
    </section>
    <hr>
